  "text": "In summary, the results of the present study can respond to our hypothesis: Other studies are necessary to confirm the validity of the results of such study on a larger sample of population; indeed, such results highlight the interest of the neurometric approach to the general issue of the PSA evaluation. Furthermore, the obtained results have shown, through the estimation of the investigated indexes (i.e., Effort Index), the occurrence of a peculiar neural activation in the prefrontal cortex in response to antismoking advertising. ere have been many studies which have demonstrated that the average neural activity in the medial prefrontal cortex (MPFC) during messaging has been associated with future healthier behaviour change in individuals (e.g., for smoking reduction [CITATION_1] , physical activity [CITATION_2] ), as well as population measures of antismoking campaigns effectiveness (e.g., online click-through-rates [CITATION_3] and calls to quit lines [CITATION_4] ). Given the multiple psychological functions supported by MPFC [CITATION_5] , examining the functional connectivity, specifically within the brain's value system can provide additional information about why and how certain types of messages, like graphic warning messages, exert their effects. e meaning of the activity in a particular region changes depending on its interactions with other key regions [CITATION_6] , and examining the coherence of activity between brain regions during the exposure to different types of messages could provide new, complementary information about brain function [CITATION_7] . In line with the importance of considering MPFC, Cooper and colleagues [CITATION_8] found that the functional connectivity within investigated region during the exposure to health messages is linked to behaviour change.",
